What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 loan listings in the dataset, with 81 features, listed between 2005 and 2014. Most features are numeric or strings, but there are some datetime and categorical type columns that may need converting.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in finding out how borrowing from friends influence on one's default rate.

update It turns out too few of the loans were funded by 5 friends or more (only 26), so we'll try to determine what factors have influence on the default rate (LoanStatus) and BorrowerAPR.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The latter columns (InvestmentFromFriendsCount and InvestmentFromFriendsAmount) would be of particular interest if we were to maintain our initial interest to investigate the correlation between being funded by friends and one's default rate. Since that is no longer the case, we expect the following to have some relation to LoanStatus:

  • BorrowerAPR,
  • EmploymentStatus,
  • DebtToIncomeRatio and
  • IncomeRange

Converting to ordered Categorical dtype¶

In [16]:
cat_order = {'IncomeRange': ['Not displayed', 'Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', 
                             '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', '$100,000+'],
            'LoanStatus': ['Cancelled', 'Past Due (>120 days)', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Past Due (16-30 days)', 
                           'Past Due (91-120 days)', 'Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (31-60 days)',
                           'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Defaulted', 'Chargedoff', 'Completed', 'Current'],
            'EmploymentStatus': ['Other', 'Not available', 'Not employed', 'Part-time', 'Self-employed',
                                 'Full-time', 'Employed', 'Retired']}
"""for column in cat_order:
    print(column)"""


for column in cat_order:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=cat_order[column])
    loans[column] = loans[column].astype(ordered_var)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

It was unusual to find out that a significant part of the loans was taken for debt consolidation purposes. In other words, borrowers were refinancing existing debts rather than borrowing for new projects or expenses.

Transformation (to log scale) was needed only for PercentFund and LoanStatus, since the count was highly concentrated on a few categories.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I had perform operations to change data types for datetime columns and also to a few of the categorical variables in order to allow further investigation of these variables later. Log scales was used for better visualization as explained on the answer right above.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We have observed that the one of the important factors for the BorrowerAPR variable is the IncomeRange of the Borrower. The higher the income, the lower the interest paid in the loan, even when we control for the debt ratio or the interest rate to be paid.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I had no idea that Income would play such an important part in BorrowerAPR. Initially, I thought that controlling for other variables that are expressed in proportions or percentages would eventually show that Income was in fact not important at all. It seems I was wrong. Although the Debt ratio tends to be higher for lower income borrowers, I decided to observe boxplots for each income range when all the ranges share the same debt ratio. Still, the summary stats for BorrowerAPR was lower for higher income borrowers.

Then I decided to tackle a possible APR rate bias. My line of thought was: maybe lower income borrowers just default more because they're charged higher rates, so they struggle because of the rate itself. So I selected only loans with lower interest rates, but still got the same trend.

Given all that, this work cannot make conclusions about causation, because none of the correlations shown here imply such a relation. We can simply say that the likelihood for default and charge-off is lower as your Income range increases and we can only speculate on the reasons that happens, but not categorically say we were able to determine them, as that would require controlled testing and a whole other approach.
